t of bodies and gender. Abject Relations departs from conventional psychotherapy approaches and offers a different "logic," one that involves the shifting forces of power, disgust, and desire and provides new ways of thinking that may have implications for future treatment regimes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAnorexia nervosaxPatientsxPsychology. 0aAnorexia nervosaxSocial aspects. 0aAnorexia nervosa. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  asocial science, anthropology, medical, health, medicine, anorexia, anorexia nervosa, eating disorder, food restriction, mental disorder, physical health, mental health, individualism, beauty, self control, autonomy, gender studies, psychotherapy, binge eating, bulimia, bulimia nervosa, body dysmorphia, body dysmorphic disorder, diet, dieting, anxiety, anxiety disorder, depression, substance abuse, food, eating, ethnography, social anthropology, public health, anorexic.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081354821040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813548210423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813548210.jpg  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK